{
  "texts": [
    "Firstly, 3D networks typically have more parameters, leading to higher computational demands and making them more challenging to optimize especially on small datasets.",
    "Additionally, powerful 2D networks pre-trained on large datasets of 2D images are readily available to use as the basis of new models via transfer learning 18, but a limited choice of 3D architectures is available in this way.",
    "Finally, since thick slice MRI data is highly anisotropic, it is not necessarily optimal to treat all three spatial dimensions equivalently within the model.",
    "Thus some authors use 2D CNNs applied to each 3D slice of the MRI, potentially with immediately adjacent slices included as additional channels in a so-called \"2.5D\" architecture.",
    "Mixed results suggest that the optimal choice of architecture may be dependent on application and training dataset [19] [20] [21]."
  ]
}